Equity ResearchAugust 27,2025

Demand signals remain rock solid with Hopper and Blackwell sold out across the board. Blackwell Ultra ramp well underway alleviating concerns of supply chain issues going forward. We see a path to $7+ in EPS next year with $8+ in C27 and continue to favor NVDA as our overall Top Pick.

October guide was in line with lowered expectations and importantly, the B300 rollout progressing smoothly, Rubin remains on track, and China licenses offer potential to add an additional $2-5B of revenue in October with upside pending demand outlook. Networking revenue tallied $7B with broad-based strength from NVLink, Spectrum-X, and Infiniband all offering a solid tailwind for gross margins. Broader demand outlook remains intact, underpinned by improvig ROI dynamics with $3M investment in GPUs now generating up to $30M in token revenues, accelerating hyperscaler Capex, and Sovereign expected to make up $20B of revenue this year. Everything remains sold-out across both Hopper and Blackwell, with one non-restricted customer even buying H20s. Plenty of runway for continued growth in both Compute and Networking as situation in China continues to work itself out.

**Better Gaming Revenue Drives July Beat: July revenue above at $46.7B (+6% Q/Q, vs St. $45.9B)**with ~$27B of Blackwell revenue (+17% Q/Q). Data Center revenue slightly below at $41.1B (+5% Q/Q, vs St. $41.3B) with Compute of $33.8B (-1% Q/Q) and Networking of $7.3B (+46% Q/Q). DC Compute revenue headwind from $4B reduction in H20 sales (sold $650M of H20 to unrestricted customer outside of China). Gaming beat at $4.3B (+14% Q/Q, vs St. $3.7B) with strong sales and increased supply of Blackwell. Automotive slightly better at $586M (+3% Q/Q, vs St. $581M) driven by strong adoption for self-driving platforms. Professional Visualization beat at $601M (+18% Q/Q, vs St. $531M) driven by acceleration of Blackwell sales in Notebook products, addressing AI workflows, real-time graphics rendering, and data simulation. OEM and Other came in better at $173M (+56% Q/Q, vs St. $113M). GMs reported slightly better at 72.7% (vs St. 72.1%) but was 72.3% excluding H20 related charges/releases, net (+100bps Q/Q). Opex reported lower at $3.8B (+6% Q/Q, vs St. $4.1B) driving OM ahead at 64.5% (vs St. 63.2%). All in, EPS beat at $1.05 (vs St. $1.00).

**October Revenue Guidance-Lighter with Upside from China: October revenue guided above at**$54.0B (+16% Q/Q, vs St.$52.7B) which does not include any H20 shipments to China ($2-5B of H20 revenue to China possible if geopolitical issues reside). We are modeling Data Center to $50.0B (+22% Q/Q, vs St. $49.8B), Gaming to $4.6B (+8% Q/Q, vs St. $4.0B), Automotive to $615M (+5% Q/Q, vs St. $626M), Professional Visualization to $613M (+2% Q/Q, vs St. $551M), and OEM/Other to $176M (+2% Q/Q, vs St. $114M). Within DC, we model Compute at $40.6B (+20% Q/Q, vs $41.0B prior) and Working at $9.4B (+30% Q/Q, vs $8.4B prior).

- Industry checks suggest further upside with beats continuing as Blackwell ramps.- Unique bottom-up approach with multiple inputs from Asian and Fubon counterparts through the supply chain (ODM, Packaging, CoWoS, etc).- See increased systems sales with the ramp of the GB200, further increasing the competitive moat.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- NVDA remains the dominant supplier of acceleration solutions in the data center.- Gaming TAM expands at a double-digit CAGR.- Auto modeled to grow conservatively, given AV ramp timing uncertainty.- Price Target: \(205\) implies 30x our CY27E EPS of \(56.82\).

- NVDA expanding its data center TAM and controlling \(80\% +\) of the DC ecosystem.- Accelerated growth in Generative AI across multiple end-markets.- Accelerated growth from Automotive, with proliferation of autonomous cars.- Gaming GPU upgrades and incremental demand.- Price Target: \(250\) implies 31x our CY27E EPS of \(58.00\).

- Emerging competitive threats from INTC, AMD, and internally designed ASICs from Hyperscalers take share and pressure ASPs.- Slowing datacenter capex spending from Enterprises and Hyperscalers.- Slower-than-expected ramp of Automotive platform.- Price Target: \(125\) implies 25x our CY27E EPS of \(55.00\).

Top Material Issue(s): 1) Product Design & Lifecycle: NVDA's GPU is the leader in graphics and parallel processing for HPC acceleration for AI workloads. NVDA estimates that its GPUs provide 20x better energy efficiency for these workloads over CPU servers. Its GPU leadership is bolstered by its extensive ecosystem, which expands the developer adoption and application/use cases. Future NVDA GPU growth will be driven by new applications such as Omniverse, a 3D simulation platform. One application of Omniverse was Earth- 2, a planned AI supercomputer dedicated to being a digital twin of Earth and simulating the impact of climate change.
Company Targets: 1) Make every new generation of GPUs faster and more energy- efficient than its predecessor.

Questions for Management: 1) What sustainability potential do you see from Earth- 2, and are you working with many climate activists on sustainability initiatives? 2) What applications near and long term are the biggest drivers for NVDA GPU adoption?
- Product ramp of Blackwell GPUs.- Increased datapoints around GB200NVL adoption.- Capex increases by hyperscaler customer base.- Automotive design wins and ramp of auto platform.

GM guide came in better at \(73.5\%\) (vs St. \(72.8\%\) ) which represents \(+80\%\) to Q/Q. Opex guided in line with Street at \(\) 4.2B(+11\%\mathrm{Q} / \mathrm{Q})\) , implying slightly higher OM of \(65.7\%\) (vs St. \(64.9\%\) ). Tax of \(16.5\%\) and other income/expense of \(\) 500M\$ nets implied head at \(\) 1.25\(\) (vs St. \(\) 1.19\$ ). Reiterated GM to exit the year in mid- 70s but raised Opex guide to \(\frac{1}{2}\) in the high 30s range Y/Y (vs mid- 30s prior).

Notable Call Details: Rubin on schedule for volume production in 2026. Recognized Blackwell revenue across all customer categories, led by large CSPs, which represented \(\sim 50\%\) of DC revenue. Singapore was \(22\%\) of total revenue and \(99\%\) of H100, H200, and Blackwell Data Center Compute revenue billed to Singapore was for orders from US- based customers. On track to achieve \(\) 20B\$ in Sovereign AI revenue this year. Expect \(\) 3- 4T\$ in AI infrastructure spend by end of decade. Spectrum- X revenue grew DD % sequentially and Y/Y and is now at \(\) 10B\$ annualized run rate (vs \(\) 8B\$ prior, \(+25\%\) Q/Q to \(\) 2.5B\$ from \(\) 2B\$ in Q2). InfiniBand nearly doubled Q/Q driven by adoption of XDR technology (2x improvement in bandwidth vs predecessor). GB300 achieves 7x faster training with FP4 than H100.

NVIDIA CorporationNVIDIA Corporation (NVDA) is a provider of visual computing technologies and the inventor of the graphics processing unit (GPU). The company's products are designed to generate graphics on workstations, personal computers, game consoles, and mobile devices. NVDA serves the entertainment and consumer market with its GeForce graphics products, the professional design and visualization market with its Quadro graphics products, the computing market with its Tesla computing solutions products, and the mobile computing market with its Tegra system- on- a- chip products.
Price Target: \(205 implies 30x\) our CY27E EPS of \(6.82.

Emerging competitive threats from INTC, AMD, and internally designed ASICs from Hyperscalers take share and pressure ASPs. Slowing datacenter capital spending from Enterprises and Hyperscalers. Slower- than- expected ramp of Automotive platform.
Price Target: \(160 implies 24x\) our CY27 EPS of \(6.53.

Share loss in consumer PC either to Intel or to ARM solutions. Unable to gain further share with Cloud customer base and/or increased competition from customers' internal efforts. Poor execution on AI roadmap and/or loss of lead customer.
Price Target: \(23 implies 27x\) our CY27E EPS of \(0.84.

Slower- than- expected share loss in datacenter. PC TAM higher on Enterprise refreshes and earlier- than- expected AI PC applications. Return to capital return commitment with dividend increase. Design wins and share gains in datacenter for parallel processing and accelerator products. AMD fumbles, leading to share gains for INTC.

Larger- than- expected share loss to AMD and ARM CPUs in datacenter. Decline in PC unit TAM and/or ARM disruption. Delays to upcoming 18A product launches and/or Foundry customer traction. Poor execution of manufacturing process technology transitions.
- Dividend cut further.
